1
00:00:01,092 --> 00:00:03,844
What if a game did not only test what you know,

2
00:00:03,844 --> 00:00:06,046
but showed how the world fits together?

3
00:00:07,055 --> 00:00:12,284
This is Webwoven, a game about finding paths
through real, named connections.

4
00:00:13,385 --> 00:00:16,596
In Single player, I choose Easy, Normal, or Hard.

5
00:00:17,239 --> 00:00:21,642
I can use the whole atlas or choose one of ten topics
for the start and goal.

6
00:00:22,468 --> 00:00:25,862
The game fixes those two points,
but not the path between them.

7
00:00:26,596 --> 00:00:29,257
I build the path one real connection at a time.

8
00:00:30,083 --> 00:00:32,009
Each card is a place I can go next.

9
00:00:32,376 --> 00:00:37,330
When I move, the map grows and keeps my path
and the choices I left behind.

10
00:00:38,064 --> 00:00:41,275
If a branch ends, Back takes me one step back.

11
00:00:42,193 --> 00:00:44,945
Three hints can help, but each costs points.

12
00:00:45,954 --> 00:00:47,881
Every card explains its connection.

13
00:00:48,706 --> 00:00:51,917
Lionel Messi connects to Rosario
because he was born there.

14
00:00:52,835 --> 00:00:55,771
I can inspect the fact and source before I move.

15
00:00:56,780 --> 00:00:58,615
Webwoven has three play modes.

16
00:00:59,165 --> 00:01:01,642
Single player lets me explore at my own speed.

17
00:01:02,376 --> 00:01:06,046
The Daily challenge gives everyone
the same round and leaderboard.

18
00:01:06,872 --> 00:01:09,991
In Multiplayer, two to four people race together.

19
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:12,651
A share link opens the Lobby.

20
00:01:13,018 --> 00:01:16,229
Players can reconnect,
and the group can vote for another round.

21
00:01:17,330 --> 00:01:20,083
I started with an idea, but no working game.

22
00:01:20,908 --> 00:01:24,945
I built the product with Codex
and GPT-5.6 Sol.

23
00:01:25,771 --> 00:01:29,807
I gave Codex goals, visual style,
and play-test feedback.

24
00:01:30,633 --> 00:01:36,229
Codex helped build the app, server, data tools,
tests, and public documents.

25
00:01:37,055 --> 00:01:43,294
It split the work into focused tasks for web,
server, data, security, and review.

26
00:01:44,211 --> 00:01:47,147
This saved time while keeping each part clear.

27
00:01:48,248 --> 00:01:51,917
I kept using GPT-5.6 after the first draft.

28
00:01:52,651 --> 00:01:57,422
I tested on desktop and phone,
then gave every problem back to Codex.

29
00:01:58,431 --> 00:02:03,000
We made the modes easier to find,
removed unfair loops and false dead ends,

30
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,500
simplified the phone screen,
kept long labels readable,

31
00:02:06,500 --> 00:02:10,358
and made the target pulse
when it comes within reach.

32
00:02:11,183 --> 00:02:13,752
I made the final product and release choices.

33
00:02:14,853 --> 00:02:18,431
AI helped build Webwoven,
but it does not play for you.

34
00:02:19,716 --> 00:02:25,771
During a round, the game makes no calls to AI,
Wikidata, Commons, or Wikipedia.

35
00:02:26,688 --> 00:02:32,743
Rules, moves, hints, scores, and winners
come from one checked local atlas.

36
00:02:33,752 --> 00:02:40,000
It contains 3,970 entities,
22,402 named connections,

37
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:44,028
and 100 checked start-and-goal rounds.

38
00:02:45,220 --> 00:02:48,248
Webwoven is live
and works on desktop and mobile.

39
00:02:48,615 --> 00:02:51,734
It needs no account
and is completely open-source.

40
00:02:52,835 --> 00:02:56,138
Connect anything,
and discover why it is connected.
